JO  - International Economic Review
JA  - International Economic Review
SP  - 1263
EP  - 1290
VL  - 60
IS  - 3
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12385
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - Abstract We build a life-cycle model of housing decisions under divorce risk that predicts that the recent increase in divorce rates leads to reduced homeownership rates. The risk of a divorce triggers a precautionary-savings motive. However, this motive is weaker when individuals can invest in owner-occupied homes because homeowners' higher savings partially substitute for precautionary savings. When young, the larger asset accumulation due to divorce-risk-induced precautionary savings enables households to buy homes earlier, whereas the presence of transaction costs leads to reduced homeownership for middle-aged and older households when divorce risk goes up.
ER  - 

